-- ===== ch02t2s1 Aufbau, Pauli & Hund — Filling Rules =====
('axai_ch02_061', 'According to the Aufbau principle, electrons fill orbitals in order of:', 'mcq', '["decreasing energy","increasing energy","increasing size only","random order"]', 'increasing energy', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Lower-energy orbitals are filled before higher-energy ones.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_062', 'Pauli''s exclusion principle implies that an orbital can hold a maximum of:', 'mcq', '["1 electron","2 electrons with opposite spins","6 electrons","2 electrons with the same spin"]', '2 electrons with opposite spins', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'No two electrons can have all four quantum numbers identical, so an orbital holds two with opposite spins.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_063', 'Hund''s rule of maximum multiplicity states that electrons occupy degenerate orbitals:', 'mcq', '["in pairs first","singly first, with parallel spins, before pairing","randomly","only in s orbitals"]', 'singly first, with parallel spins, before pairing', 'easy', 3, 'both', 'Each orbital of a subshell is singly filled with parallel spins before any pairing occurs.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_064', 'According to the (n+l) rule, which orbital is filled first?', 'mcq', '["3d","4s","4p","both at once"]', '4s', 'easy', 3, 'both', '4s has n+l = 4, lower than 3d (n+l = 5), so 4s fills first.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_065', 'In the normal filling order, the orbital filled immediately after 3p is:', 'mcq', '["3d","4s","4p","4d"]', '4s', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'After 3p the next orbital by energy is 4s.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_066', 'According to Pauli''s principle, two electrons in the same orbital must have:', 'mcq', '["the same spin","opposite spins","zero spin","parallel spins"]', 'opposite spins', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Paired electrons in one orbital differ in spin quantum number.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_067', 'The maximum number of unpaired electrons possible in a p subshell is:', 'mcq', '["1","2","3","6"]', '3', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'A p subshell has 3 orbitals, each able to hold one unpaired electron.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_068', 'The (n+l) value for a 3d orbital is:', 'mcq', '["3","4","5","6"]', '5', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'n + l = 3 + 2 = 5.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_069', 'When two orbitals have the same (n+l) value, the one filled first is the one with:', 'mcq', '["higher n","lower n","higher l","lower l"]', 'lower n', 'easy', 3, 'both', 'For equal (n+l), the orbital with the lower n is filled first.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_070', 'A configuration that violates Pauli''s exclusion principle would show:', 'mcq', '["two electrons in one orbital with opposite spins","two electrons in one orbital with the same spin","a singly occupied orbital","a fully filled subshell"]', 'two electrons in one orbital with the same spin', 'easy', 3, 'both', 'Two electrons in the same orbital cannot have identical spin.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_071', 'The number of unpaired electrons in nitrogen (Z = 7) is:', 'mcq', '["1","2","3","5"]', '3', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'N: 1s²2s²2p³ — the three 2p electrons are unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_072', 'The number of unpaired electrons in oxygen (Z = 8) is:', 'mcq', '["1","2","3","4"]', '2', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'O: 1s²2s²2p⁴ — two of the 2p orbitals hold unpaired electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_073', 'The orbital filled immediately after 4s is:', 'mcq', '["4p","3d","4d","5s"]', '3d', 'medium', 3, 'both', 'After 4s (n+l = 4) comes 3d (n+l = 5).', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_074', 'The total number of electrons that a 3d subshell can accommodate is:', 'mcq', '["2","6","10","14"]', '10', 'medium', 3, 'both', 'd subshell: 5 orbitals × 2 = 10 electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_075', 'For carbon (Z = 6), Hund''s rule predicts the 2p electrons are arranged as:', 'mcq', '["paired in one orbital","two orbitals singly occupied with parallel spins","three orbitals singly occupied","all in the 2s orbital"]', 'two orbitals singly occupied with parallel spins', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'The two 2p electrons occupy separate orbitals with parallel spins.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_076', 'The (n+l) values of the 4p and 3d orbitals respectively are:', 'mcq', '["4 and 5","5 and 5","5 and 4","6 and 5"]', '5 and 5', 'medium', 5, 'both', '4p: 4+1 = 5; 3d: 3+2 = 5 — both equal 5.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_077', 'According to the (n+l) rule, which orbital is filled first, 4f or 5p?', 'mcq', '["4f","5p","5d","both together"]', '5p', 'medium', 5, 'both', '5p has n+l = 6, lower than 4f (n+l = 7), so 5p fills first.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_078', 'The number of unpaired electrons in phosphorus (Z = 15) is:', 'mcq', '["1","2","3","5"]', '3', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'P: [Ne]3s²3p³ — the three 3p electrons are unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_079', 'As a consequence of Pauli''s principle, the maximum number of electrons with the same spin in a single orbital is:', 'mcq', '["0","1","2","3"]', '1', 'medium', 3, 'both', 'An orbital can hold at most one electron of each spin, so only one with a given spin.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_080', 'The correct order of increasing energy for the orbitals 4s, 3d and 4p is:', 'mcq', '["3d < 4s < 4p","4s < 3d < 4p","4s < 4p < 3d","4p < 3d < 4s"]', '4s < 3d < 4p', 'medium', 5, 'both', 'By the (n+l) rule the order is 4s (4) < 3d (5) < 4p (5, but higher n than 3d... energy 4s<3d<4p).', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_081', 'The number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of chromium (Z = 24) is:', 'mcq', '["1","4","5","6"]', '6', 'hard', 8, 'jee', 'Cr is [Ar]3d⁵4s¹ (anomalous): five 3d plus one 4s electron = 6 unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_082', 'The number of unpaired electrons in iron (Z = 26) is:', 'mcq', '["2","3","4","6"]', '4', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Fe: [Ar]3d⁶4s² — 3d⁶ has one paired plus four unpaired electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_083', 'Copper (Z = 29) has an anomalous configuration. Its number of unpaired electrons is:', 'mcq', '["0","1","2","5"]', '1', 'hard', 8, 'jee', 'Cu is [Ar]3d¹⁰4s¹: the filled 3d¹⁰ leaves only the single 4s electron unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_084', 'The number of unpaired electrons in manganese (Z = 25) is:', 'mcq', '["3","5","6","7"]', '5', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Mn: [Ar]3d⁵4s² — all five 3d electrons are unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_085', 'For scandium (Z = 21), the orbital that receives the last electron in the ground state is:', 'mcq', '["4s","3d","4p","3p"]', '3d', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Sc is [Ar]3d¹4s²; 4s fills before 3d, so the last electron enters 3d.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_086', 'According to Hund''s rule, the maximum number of unpaired electrons in a d subshell is:', 'mcq', '["3","5","7","10"]', '5', 'hard', 6, 'jee', 'A d subshell has 5 orbitals, each can hold one unpaired electron → 5.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_087', 'Which of the following ground-state configurations violates the Aufbau principle?', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3d¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3d¹', 'hard', 7, 'jee', '3d should not be filled before 3p (and 4s); the correct next orbital after 3s is 3p.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_088', 'The number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of vanadium (Z = 23) is:', 'mcq', '["1","2","3","5"]', '3', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'V: [Ar]3d³4s² — the three 3d electrons are unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_089', 'The number of unpaired electrons in nickel (Z = 28) is:', 'mcq', '["0","2","4","6"]', '2', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Ni: [Ar]3d⁸4s² — 3d⁸ leaves two unpaired electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
('axai_ch02_090', 'Which of the following atoms has zero unpaired electrons in its ground state?', 'mcq', '["N","O","Ne","Na"]', 'Ne', 'hard', 6, 'both', 'Ne (1s²2s²2p⁶) is fully paired; N has 3, O has 2 and Na has 1 unpaired electron.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s1'),
-- ===== ch02t2s2 Electronic Configurations of Atoms & Ions =====
('axai_ch02_091', 'The ground-state electronic configuration of carbon (Z = 6) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p²","1s² 2s² 2p⁴","1s² 2s⁴","1s² 2s² 2p⁶"]', '1s² 2s² 2p²', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Six electrons fill 1s², 2s², then 2p².', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_092', 'The ground-state configuration of sodium (Z = 11) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶","1s² 2s² 2p⁵ 3s²","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Eleven electrons fill up to 3s¹.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_093', 'The ground-state configuration of oxygen (Z = 8) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p²","1s² 2s² 2p⁴","1s² 2s² 2p⁶","1s² 2s⁴ 2p²"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁴', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Eight electrons give 1s² 2s² 2p⁴.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_094', 'The number of valence-shell electrons in nitrogen (Z = 7) is:', 'mcq', '["2","3","5","7"]', '5', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'N: 2s²2p³, so the n = 2 valence shell has 5 electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_095', 'The ground-state configuration of neon (Z = 10) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁴","1s² 2s² 2p⁶","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²","1s² 2s² 2p⁵"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶', 'easy', 1, 'both', 'Ten electrons completely fill 1s, 2s and 2p.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_096', 'The ground-state configuration of fluorine (Z = 9) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁵","1s² 2s² 2p⁶","1s² 2s² 2p⁴","1s² 2s¹ 2p⁶"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁵', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Nine electrons give 1s² 2s² 2p⁵.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_097', 'The ground-state configuration of magnesium (Z = 12) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3p²","1s² 2s² 2p⁴ 3s²"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Twelve electrons fill up to 3s².', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_098', 'The element with configuration 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ is:', 'mcq', '["neon","argon","krypton","chlorine"]', 'argon', 'easy', 2, 'both', '18 electrons in that configuration correspond to argon (Z = 18).', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_099', 'The number of valence electrons in chlorine (Z = 17) is:', 'mcq', '["5","6","7","8"]', '7', 'easy', 2, 'both', 'Cl: [Ne]3s²3p⁵ — the n = 3 valence shell has 7 electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_100', 'The configuration 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹ represents:', 'mcq', '["lithium","sodium","magnesium","neon"]', 'sodium', 'easy', 2, 'both', '11 electrons in that configuration correspond to sodium (Z = 11).', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_101', 'The electronic configuration of the Na⁺ ion (Z = 11) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁵","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'Na loses its 3s¹ electron, leaving the neon configuration.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_102', 'The electronic configuration of the chloride ion Cl⁻ (Z = 17) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁵","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁴","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'Cl gains one electron to reach the argon configuration.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_103', 'The electronic configuration of the O²⁻ ion (Z = 8) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁴","1s² 2s² 2p⁶","1s² 2s² 2p⁵","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'O gains two electrons to reach the neon configuration.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_104', 'The ground-state configuration of potassium (Z = 19) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 3d¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁵ 4s²","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s¹', 'medium', 4, 'both', '4s fills before 3d, so the 19th electron enters 4s.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_105', 'Which of the following ions has the same configuration as argon?', 'mcq', '["Na⁺","Mg²⁺","Ca²⁺","Li⁺"]', 'Ca²⁺', 'medium', 5, 'both', 'Ca²⁺ (20 − 2 = 18 electrons) is isoelectronic with argon.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_106', 'The ground-state configuration of calcium (Z = 20) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 3d²","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s²","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁴ 4s²","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s¹"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p⁶ 4s²', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'Twenty electrons fill up to 4s².', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_107', 'The electronic configuration of the Mg²⁺ ion (Z = 12) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s²","1s² 2s² 2p⁴","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'Mg loses both 3s electrons to reach the neon configuration.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_108', 'The number of unpaired electrons in the Fe³⁺ ion (Z = 26) is:', 'mcq', '["3","4","5","6"]', '5', 'medium', 6, 'jee', 'Fe³⁺ is [Ar]3d⁵, so all five 3d electrons are unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_109', 'Which of the following species is isoelectronic with neon (10 electrons)?', 'mcq', '["F⁻","Cl⁻","Na","Mg"]', 'F⁻', 'medium', 5, 'both', 'F⁻ has 9 + 1 = 10 electrons, matching neon.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_110', 'The ground-state configuration of aluminium (Z = 13) is:', 'mcq', '["1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p¹","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s³","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p³","1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3p³"]', '1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p¹', 'medium', 4, 'both', 'Thirteen electrons fill up to 3p¹.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_111', 'The ground-state configuration of chromium (Z = 24) is:', 'mcq', '["[Ar] 3d⁴ 4s²","[Ar] 3d⁵ 4s¹","[Ar] 3d⁶ 4s⁰","[Ar] 3d⁵ 4s²"]', '[Ar] 3d⁵ 4s¹', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Cr adopts the anomalous [Ar]3d⁵4s¹ for a stable half-filled 3d.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_112', 'The ground-state configuration of copper (Z = 29) is:', 'mcq', '["[Ar] 3d⁹ 4s²","[Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s¹","[Ar] 3d⁸ 4s²","[Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s²"]', '[Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s¹', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Cu adopts the anomalous [Ar]3d¹⁰4s¹ for a stable fully-filled 3d.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_113', 'The electronic configuration of the Cu²⁺ ion (Z = 29) is:', 'mcq', '["[Ar] 3d⁹","[Ar] 3d¹⁰","[Ar] 3d⁸ 4s¹","[Ar] 3d⁷"]', '[Ar] 3d⁹', 'hard', 8, 'jee', 'From Cu [Ar]3d¹⁰4s¹, removing two electrons (4s then one 3d) gives [Ar]3d⁹.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_114', 'The number of unpaired electrons in the Mn²⁺ ion (Z = 25) is:', 'mcq', '["3","4","5","6"]', '5', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Mn²⁺ is [Ar]3d⁵ (4s² removed), so all five 3d electrons are unpaired.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_115', 'Which of the following is isoelectronic with Ca²⁺?', 'mcq', '["Ar","K⁺","Cl⁻","all of these"]', 'all of these', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Ca²⁺, Ar, K⁺ and Cl⁻ all have 18 electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_116', 'The electronic configuration of the Fe²⁺ ion (Z = 26) is:', 'mcq', '["[Ar] 3d⁶","[Ar] 3d⁴ 4s²","[Ar] 3d⁵ 4s¹","[Ar] 3d⁸"]', '[Ar] 3d⁶', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'From Fe [Ar]3d⁶4s², the two 4s electrons are removed first → [Ar]3d⁶.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_117', 'The number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of cobalt (Z = 27) is:', 'mcq', '["2","3","4","5"]', '3', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'Co: [Ar]3d⁷4s² — 3d⁷ leaves three unpaired electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_118', 'An ion M²⁺ has the configuration [Ar] 3d⁵. The atomic number of M is:', 'mcq', '["23","25","26","27"]', '25', 'hard', 8, 'jee', '[Ar]3d⁵ has 23 electrons; the neutral atom has 23 + 2 = 25 (manganese).', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_119', 'The electronic configuration of the Zn²⁺ ion (Z = 30) is:', 'mcq', '["[Ar] 3d¹⁰","[Ar] 3d⁸","[Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s²","[Ar] 3d⁹ 4s¹"]', '[Ar] 3d¹⁰', 'hard', 7, 'jee', 'From Zn [Ar]3d¹⁰4s², removing the two 4s electrons gives [Ar]3d¹⁰.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2'),
('axai_ch02_120', 'Which of the following pairs is isoelectronic?', 'mcq', '["Na⁺ and F⁻","K⁺ and Cl","Ca²⁺ and S","Mg²⁺ and O"]', 'Na⁺ and F⁻', 'hard', 7, 'both', 'Na⁺ (10 e) and F⁻ (10 e) have the same number of electrons.', 'chem', 'ch02', 'ch02t2', 'ch02t2s2')
on conflict (id) do nothing;
